<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-647-050  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 647 050.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Business Week  July 23 1990 n3170 p41(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It's crunch time for Europe's high-tech giants. (computer andelectronics industries) (Commentary) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Levine, Jonathan B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Europe's computer and semiconductor industries are experiencingsignificant losses despite trade barriers and cooperativeagreements designed to fight foreign competition.andP;  Europeancompanies would realize greater success if they used cooperatedmore, such as with the $4 billion, eight-year Joint EuropeanSubmicron Silicon project (JESSI).andP;  Siemens AG, for example, isrecovering from trouble it had in developing memory chips bylicensing needed technology from Toshiba Corp. Philips, the Dutchelectronics firm, is expected to lose about $1 billion in 1990, inpart because of its tendency to work in isolation.andP;  Thesemiconductor and computer industries can become stronger if thenumber of companies is consolidated through mergers and jointproduction.andP;  Competition is expected to increase after thecreation of a single European market in 1992.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EuropeComputer industrySemiconductor industryCooperationIndustry AnalysisForeign CompetitionSingle European Market.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>